    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Mothers at Work</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sima Shelly Toussi letter on Cameron Stracher's Sept 2 article lauds workplace child care and other corporate policies that enable women with families to work</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Child Care and Other Traps,'' by Cameron Stracher (Op-Ed, Sept. 2):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Child Care and Other Traps,'' by Cameron Stracher (Op-Ed, Sept. 2):</p>
        <p>Mr. Stracher laments that family-friendly corporate policies like child care at the workplace blur divisions between work and home life, making women ''less likely to go home to have dinner with their husbands.''</p>
        <p>Yet many women must work full time to provide for their families or to remain competitive in their fields. Mothers who bring their children to work can breast-feed during lunch, use a nursery service that is probably cheaper than private care and work a full day.</p>
        <p>Mr. Stracher's contention that people must make the ''hard choice'' between ''work or family'' would prevent women with families from becoming partners at law firms or tenured faculty members -- a choice men rarely have to make.</p>
        <p>SIMA SHELLY TOUSSI  New York, Sept. 5, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a student at Dartmouth Medical School.</p>
      </block>
